WEBVTT

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:04.400
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>the situation</i> in Spanish?

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:06.240
<v Student><b>La situación</b>.

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.120
<v Teacher>Good. <b>-ión</b> is a feminine ending,

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:14.960
<v Teacher>so the word takes <b>la</b> for <i>the</i>. <b>La situación</b>. Good.

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:25.439
<v Teacher>Now in Spanish, adjectives are describing words. Adjectives are words that describe, like <i>big</i> or <i>yellow</i> or <i>happy</i>.

00:00:25.439 --> 00:00:29.860
<v Teacher>Words that we can put <i>is</i> in front of are adjectives, describing words.

00:00:29.860 --> 00:00:35.400
<v Teacher>These words come after the noun they describe in Spanish.

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:42.040
<v Teacher>So instead of saying, "the global situation" for example, you say "the situation global".

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:46.160
<v Teacher>There's a bit of flexibility for emphasis as well,

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:50.480
<v Teacher>but the normal standard position is to come after the noun.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:53.840
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>the global situation</i>?

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:57.460
<v Student><b>La situación global</b>.

00:00:57.460 --> 00:00:59.940
<v Teacher>Good. <b>La situación global</b>.

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:03.460
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>digital camera</i>? <i>Digital camera</i>:

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:05.620
<v Student><b>Cámara digital</b>.

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.180
<v Teacher>Yeah. <b>Cámara digital</b>. Good.

00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:09.860
<v Teacher><b>Cámara</b> is feminine,

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:15.400
<v Teacher>so <i>a digital camera</i> is <b>una cámara digital</b>.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:18.440
<v Teacher>So we have <b>la</b> for <i>the</i>, and <b>una</b> for <i>a</i>.

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:24.680
<v Teacher>So how would you say, <i>I want to buy a digital camera</i>? What was the verb <i>to buy</i>?

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:25.940
<v Student><b>Comprar</b>.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:30.820
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>I want to buy a digital camera</i>:

00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:35.140
<v Student><b>Quiero comprar una cámara digital</b>.

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:39.200
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Quiero comprar una cámara digital</b>.

00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:42.799
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I want to buy the digital camera</i>?

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.799
<v Student><b>Quiero comprar la cámara digital</b>.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.159
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Quiero comprar la cámara digital</b>.

00:01:50.159 --> 00:01:58.479
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to say, <i>I want to buy it</i> and with the <i>it</i>, you meant the digital camera?

00:01:58.479 --> 00:02:00.240
<v Student>Quiero comprarla.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:00.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:02.000
<v Teacher>So this lies it

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:07.840
<v Teacher>There's a lot of words in Spanish for car depending on where you are.

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:14.920
<v Teacher>It's one of the words that changes a lot between the dialects, but I think everybody understands all of the words that are heard.

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:19.000
<v Teacher>You might hear <b>coche</b>, which is related to <i>coach</i>;

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.280
<v Teacher><b>carro</b>, which of course is <i>car</i>, <b>carro</b>,

00:02:22.280 --> 00:02:27.620
<v Teacher>so we have two <i>r</i>'s in <b>carro</b>, that's why we have this rolling <i>r</i>. You might hear <b>auto</b>,

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:30.580
<v Teacher>where do you think <b>auto</b> comes from?

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:31.700
<v Student>Automobile.

00:02:31.700 --> 00:02:36.980
<v Teacher>Of course, and it exists: <b>automóbil</b>. But people will say <b>auto</b>.

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:41.280
<v Teacher>You might even hear <b>máquina</b>, which means <i>machine</i>.

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:43.680
<v Teacher>So <i>machine</i>, the car, <b>máquina</b>.

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:52.880
<v Teacher>This is another example of the <i>q-u</i> spelling producing <i>k</i> sound. <i>M-a-q-u-i-n-a</i>. <b>Máquina</b>.

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:53.760
<v Student><b>Máquina</b>.

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:58.960
<v Teacher>Good. So there's a few words there for car, and you might hear others as well.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:03.520
<v Teacher><b>Coche</b> is masculine, so how would you say <i>the car</i>?

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:03.840
<v Student><b>El coche</b>.

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:06.400
<v Teacher>Good. <i>A</i> for masculine words is <b>un</b>. <i>U-n</i>. <b>Un</b>.

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:09.360
<v Teacher>So, <i>a car</i>:

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:10.560
<v Student><b>Un coche</b>.

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:14.239
<v Teacher><i>The machine</i>? Does <b>máquina</b> look masculine or feminine?

00:03:14.239 --> 00:03:14.959
<v Student>Feminine.

00:03:14.959 --> 00:03:16.799
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>the machine</i>:

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:18.400
<v Student><b>La máquina</b>.

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:19.200
<v Teacher><b>La máquina</b>.

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:20.640
<v Teacher><i>A machine</i>:

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:22.000
<v Student><b>Una máquina</b>.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.440
<v Teacher>Good. And does <b>carro</b> look masculine or feminine?

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:27.380
<v Student>Masculine.

00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:30.100
<v Teacher>Good. So <i>the car</i>:

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:31.220
<v Teacher>El carro.

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:33.300
<v Teacher>A car.

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:34.500
<v Student>Un carro.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:35.460
<v Teacher>Un carro.

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.000
<v Student><b>El carro</b>.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
<v Teacher><b>El carro</b>. <i>A car</i>:

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.460
<v Student><b>Un carro</b>.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:40.180
<v Teacher><b>Un carro</b>. Good. So it's the noun that has the gender, not the object.

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:45.340
<v Teacher>Of course it's not the car that is masculine or feminine, it's the noun, it's the word itself.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:50.860
<v Teacher>So even though all of these words refer to car, some are masculine and some are feminine.

00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:54.300
<v Teacher><i>Big</i>, in Spanish, is <b>grande</b>, <b>grande</b>.

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:59.020
<v Teacher>Of course we can relate this to <i>grand</i> in English, <b>grande</b>.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:03.980
<v Teacher>So using any of these words that you like, how would you say, <i>the big car</i>?

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:05.780
<v Student><b>La máquina grande</b>.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:07.860
<v Teacher>Good. <b>La máquina grande</b>.

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:11.620
<v Teacher>So <b>la máquina grande</b>, <b>el auto grande</b>.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:18.500
<v Teacher>Now if you say <i>the big cars</i>, this adjective is also going to become plural.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.840
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>the house</i>?

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:21.720
<v Student><b>La casa</b>.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.760
<v Teacher>Good. And how was <i>the houses</i>?

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:25.960
<v Student><b>Las casas</b>.

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:29.000
<v Teacher>Good, so <b>la</b> also became plural. So

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:35.639
<v Teacher><b>las casas</b>, if you say <i>the big houses</i>, <i>big</i> is also going to become plural.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:36.600
<v Student><b>Grandes</b>.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:38.919
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>the big houses</i>?

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:40.879
<v Student><b>Las casas grandes</b>.

00:04:40.879 --> 00:04:43.280
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Las casas grandes</b>.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:46.400
<v Teacher><i>The big car</i>, using <b>auto</b>:

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:48.000
<v Student><b>El auto grande</b>.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
<v Teacher>Good. <b>El auto grande</b>. <i>The cars</i>,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:05:01.720
<v Teacher>using <b>auto</b>, so a masculine word, you say <b>los autos</b>. So <b>el</b> becomes <b>los</b> in plural. So how would you say <i>the big cars</i>?

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:04.580
<v Student><b>Los autos grandes</b>.

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:09.140
<v Teacher><b>Los autos grandes</b>. <b>Los carros grandes</b>. Good.

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:13.300
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>Can you see the big car?</i>

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:15.940
<v Teacher>you can say, <i>can you see</i>?,

00:05:15.940 --> 00:05:18.900
<v Teacher>or in Spanish you can just say, <i>do you see</i>?

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:22.100
<v Teacher>We kind of overuse this <i>can</i> a lot in English.

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:24.660
<v Teacher>So, <i>Do you see the big car</i>?:

00:05:24.940 --> 00:05:26.300
<v Student>You informal?

00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:30.139
<v Student>¿<b>Ves el coche grande</b>?

00:05:30.139 --> 00:05:34.620
<v Teacher>Good. You needed some time there to look at <b>ves</b>.

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:40.340
<v Teacher>And this was the more common way actually, of saying it in Spanish: ¿<b>Ves el auto grande</b>?

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:48.780
<v Teacher>But, if you didn't have that time to think about it, even though it's more natural to say it like this it really doesn't matter; you can say <i>can you see</i>…

00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:57.500
<v Teacher>Now you would probably be quicker at building <i>can you see</i> than <i>you see</i> because <i>can</i> is something very common that you're going to be using all the time.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:03.080
<v Teacher>So in conversation, where you just want to get the meaning across, you might want to use this.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:06.280
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>can you see the big car</i>?:

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:08.980
<v Student>¿<b>Puedes ver el coche grande</b>?

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:19.140
<v Teacher>Good. So <b>puedo</b>, <b>quiero</b>, <b>tengo que</b>, <b>debo</b>, these verbs that are followed by "to" versions that you're going to be using a lot,

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:23.300
<v Teacher>even though the sentence is longer, they are short cuts. They are short cuts in thought.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:29.380
<v Teacher>And once you become very confident with that, you're going to start noticing that people say things differently to you.

00:06:29.380 --> 00:06:33.380
<v Teacher>So instead of <i>I can't find it</i>, <i>I don't find it</i>.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:36.380
<v Teacher>You will notice that yourself and your speech will adjust,

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:42.540
<v Teacher>but in the beginning what you're trying to do is to be conversational and correct structurally.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:49.600
<v Teacher>Once you get over that hurdle of being communicative, you're going to start noticing that people say things differently to you.

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:53.680
<v Teacher>So instead of <i>I can't find it</i>, <i>I don't find it</i>.

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:58.040
<v Teacher>So you could say, <i>I can't find it</i>. How would you say <i>I can't find it</i>?

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:00.760
<v Teacher>What was <i>to find</i>, or <i>to encounter</i>?

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:02.120
<v Student><b>Encontrar</b>.

00:07:02.120 --> 00:07:05.320
<v Teacher><b>Encontrar</b>. So say <i>I can't find it</i>:

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:09.060
<v Student><b>No puedo encontrarlo</b>.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:12.659
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No puedo encontrarlo</b>.

00:07:12.659 --> 00:07:16.340
<v Teacher>This would be the short cut even though it's longer,

00:07:16.340 --> 00:07:25.020
<v Teacher>it's much easier to build <b>no puedo encontrarlo</b> because <b>puedo</b> is something you're going to be using all the time, and <b>encontrar</b> is in the "to" form.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:27.259
<v Teacher><i>I don't find it</i>, how would that be?

00:07:29.699 --> 00:07:31.139
<v Student><b>No lo encuentro</b>.

00:07:31.139 --> 00:07:33.540
<v Teacher><b>No lo encuentro</b>. Good.

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:45.919
<v Teacher>So it's very useful to bear in mind these verbs like <b>puedo</b>, <b>debo</b>, which we can use with "to" forms which give us a short cut and allow us to get conversational very quickly.

00:07:45.919 --> 00:07:48.800
<v Teacher>What was <i>to remain</i>?

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:50.300
<v Student><b>Quedar</b>.

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:51.900
<v Teacher><b>Quedar</b>. Good.

00:07:51.900 --> 00:07:55.180
<v Teacher>And <i>I remain myself</i> is how we get the meaning of <i>I stay</i>.

00:07:55.180 --> 00:07:57.180
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>I stay</i>?

00:07:57.180 --> 00:08:01.340
<v Student><b>Quedarme</b>.

00:08:01.340 --> 00:08:05.500
<v Teacher><i>I remain myself</i>. <i>I remain myself</i>. What's <i>to remain</i>?

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:06.500
<v Student><b>Quedar</b>.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.280
<v Teacher>What's <i>I remain</i>?

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:09.240
<v Student><b>Quedo</b>.

00:08:09.240 --> 00:08:11.720
<v Teacher>Uh-huh. What's <i>I remain myself</i>?

00:08:11.720 --> 00:08:13.080
<v Student><b>Me quedo</b>.

00:08:13.080 --> 00:08:14.440
<v Teacher>What was happening?

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:20.599
<v Student>I was thinking "okay the <b>me</b> should go first, but it can't go first because the verb is in the 'to' form".

00:08:20.599 --> 00:08:23.780
<v Student>And I just got stuck.

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:30.020
<v Teacher>Well you start when you're building the sentence with the verb. With who's doing that.

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:32.640
<v Teacher>So if you start with that, then it's not in the "to" form anymore.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:36.400
<v Teacher>The order of thought is very important; the verb is the backbone.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:41.200
<v Teacher>That's the first place you want to go: <b>quedo</b>. <i>I remain myself</i>: <b>me quedo</b>.

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:43.540
<v Teacher>So <b>me quedo</b> is <i>I stay</i>.

00:08:43.540 --> 00:08:47.780
<v Teacher>The word for <i>red</i> in Spanish is <b>rojo</b>. <b>Rojo</b>.

00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:52.580
<v Teacher>This is spelled <i>r-o-j-o</i>. And <i>j</i>'s in Spanish are pronounced

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:54.759
<v Teacher>like this, <b>rojo</b>.

00:08:54.759 --> 00:08:55.399
<v Student><b>Rojo</b>.

00:08:55.399 --> 00:08:59.480
<v Teacher>And we have the initial <i>r</i>, so if you can do it, it will be the rolling <i>r</i>.

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:00.440
<v Teacher><b>Rojo</b>.

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:01.399
<v Student><b>Rojo</b>.

00:09:01.399 --> 00:09:06.640
<v Teacher>Good. So how would you say <i>I'm staying in the red car</i>?

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:08.960
<v Teacher><i>I'm staying in the car red</i>.

00:09:08.960 --> 00:09:12.000
<v Teacher>The word for <i>in</i> is <b>en</b>. <i>E-n</i>.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.600
<v Teacher>So let's divide it up. <i>I'm staying</i>, only think about that bit.

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:16.960
<v Teacher><i>I'm staying</i>, <i>I remain myself</i>:

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:19.460
<v Student><b>Me quedo</b>.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:20.900
<v Teacher><i>In</i>:

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:21.400
<v Student><b>En</b>.

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:26.980
<v Teacher><i>The red car</i>, <i>the car red</i>. And let's use the word <b>auto</b> for car for now.

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:31.220
<v Teacher>So <i>I'm staying in the red car</i>, <i>the car red</i>:

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:35.279
<v Student><b>Me quedo en el auto rojo</b>.

00:09:35.279 --> 00:09:38.720
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Me quedo en el auto rojo</b>. Good.

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:42.520
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I have stayed in the red car</i>? <i>I have stayed</i>,

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:46.840
<v Teacher><i>I have remained myself in the red car</i>. Again we want to divide it up.

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:51.320
<v Teacher><i>I have remained myself</i>. There's a lot to think about there, in that first bit.

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:54.699
<v Student><b>Me he quedado</b>.

00:09:54.699 --> 00:09:57.339
<v Teacher>Uh-huh. <i>In the red car</i>:

00:09:57.500 --> 00:10:00.220
<v Student><b>En el auto rojo</b>.

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:03.860
<v Teacher>Good. How would you say <i>I have bought a red car</i>?

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:06.020
<v Teacher>What is the verb <i>to buy</i>?

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:08.900
<v Student><b>Comprer</b>.

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:09.940
<v Teacher><b>Comprar</b>.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:10.900
<v Student><b>Comprar</b>. <b>Comprar</b>.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:15.980
<v Teacher><b>Comprar</b>. So <i>I have bought a red car</i>, and let's use <b>auto</b>.

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:19.420
<v Teacher><i>I have bought a red car</i>:

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:23.899
<v Student><b>He comprado un auto rojo</b>.

00:10:23.899 --> 00:10:29.420
<v Teacher>Good. <b>He comprado un</b>, (masculine word), <b>un</b>, <b>un auto rojo</b>.

00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:32.860
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I have bought myself a red car</i>?

00:10:33.660 --> 00:10:38.780
<v Student><b>Me he comprado un auto rojo</b>.

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:44.700
<v Teacher><b>Me he comprado un auto rojo</b>. <i>I have bought myself a red car</i>. Very good.

